{"action": "edit", "code": "def is_55_has_four_non_black_neighbors(input, position, color):\n    if input[position] == black:\n        return False\n    neighbors = input[max(0, position[0] - 2):position[0] + 3, max(0, position[1] - 2):position[1] + 3]\n    return np.sum(neighbors == color) == 3\ndef change_neighbor(input: np.ndarray, position: Tuple[int, int]) -> np.ndarray:\n    \"\"\"\n    This function takes a 2D numpy array and a position as input and changes the color of the position's 3x3 neighborhood according to the following rules:\n    - If the upper left corner is not black, color the lower right corner the same color.\n    - If the top right corner is not black, color the bottom left the same color.\n    - If the bottom left corner is not black, color the top right corner the same color.\n    - If the bottom right corner is not black, color the top left corner the same color.\n\n    Args:\n    input: A 2D numpy array representing the input grid.\n    position: A tuple representing the position to change.\n\n    Returns:\n    A 2D numpy array with the color of the position's 3x3 neighborhood changed according to the rules above.\n    \"\"\"\n    color = input[position]\n    if position[0] > 0 and position[1] > 0 and (input[position[0] - 1][position[1] - 1] != black):\n        input[position[0] + 1][position[1] + 1] = input[position[0] - 1][position[1] - 1]\n    if position[0] > 0 and position[1] < input.shape[1] - 1 and (input[position[0] - 1][position[1] + 1] != black):\n        input[position[0] + 1][position[1] - 1] = input[position[0] - 1][position[1] + 1]\n    if position[0] < input.shape[0] - 1 and position[1] > 0 and (input[position[0] + 1][position[1] - 1] != black):\n        input[position[0] - 1][position[1] + 1] = input[position[0] + 1][position[1] - 1]\n    if position[0] < input.shape[0] - 1 and position[1] < input.shape[1] - 1 and (input[position[0] + 1][position[1] + 1] != black):\n        input[position[0] - 1][position[1] - 1] = input[position[0] + 1][position[1] + 1]\n    return input\ndef find_non_black_color(input: np.ndarray) -> int:\n    \"\"\"\n    This function takes a 2D numpy array as input and returns the color in the input, which is not black.\n\n    Args:\n    input: A 2D numpy array representing the input grid.\n\n    Returns:\n    An integer representing the color in the input, which is not black.\n    \"\"\"\n    colors, counts = np.unique(input, return_counts=True)\n    non_black_colors = colors[colors != black]\n    if len(non_black_colors) == 1:\n        return non_black_colors[0]\n    else:\n        raise ValueError('Input contains more than one non-black color.')\ndef main(input):\n    positions = find_black_position_with_three_non_black_neighbors(input)\n    origin_color = find_non_black_color(input)\n    input = color_positions(input, positions, origin_color + 1)\n    for i in range(input.shape[0]):\n        for j in range(input.shape[1]):\n            if is_black_with_one_non_black_neighbor_of_color(input, (i, j), origin_color + 1) and is_55_has_four_non_black_neighbors(input, (i, j), origin_color):\n                input = color_positions(input, [(i, j)], origin_color + 1)\n    changed = True\n    while True:\n        changed = False\n        for i in range(input.shape[0]):\n            for j in range(input.shape[1]):\n                if is_color_with_two_non_black_neighbors_of_color(input, (i, j), origin_color + 1):\n                    input = change_neighbor(input, (i, j))\n                    changed = True\n    input = color_positions(input, positions, origin_color)\n    input = change_color(input, origin_color + 1, origin_color)\n    return input\ndef is_color_with_two_non_black_neighbors_of_color(input: np.ndarray, position: Tuple[int, int], color: int) -> bool:\n    \"\"\"\n    This function takes a 2D numpy array, a position, and a color as input and returns True if the position is not black and its 3x3 neighborhood contains only two non-black positions which are equal to the given color.\n\n    Args:\n    input: A 2D numpy array representing the input grid.\n    position: A tuple representing the position to check.\n    color: An integer representing the color to check.\n\n    Returns:\n    A boolean value indicating whether the position is not black and its 3x3 neighborhood contains only two non-black positions which are equal to the given color.\n    \"\"\"\n    if input[position] == black:\n        return False\n    neighbors = input[position[0] - 1:position[0] + 2, position[1] - 1:position[1] + 2]\n    return np.sum(neighbors != black) == 2 and np.sum(neighbors == color) == 2\ndef color_positions(input: np.ndarray, positions: Tuple[Tuple[int, int]], color: int) -> np.ndarray:\n    \"\"\"\n    This function takes a 2D numpy array, a list of positions, and a color as input and returns a new 2D numpy array where all positions in the list are changed to the given color.\n\n    Args:\n    input: A 2D numpy array representing the input grid.\n    positions: A list of tuples representing the positions to change.\n    color: An integer representing the new color.\n\n    Returns:\n    A 2D numpy array where all positions in the list are changed to the given color.\n    \"\"\"\n    for pos in positions:\n        input[pos] = color\n    return input\ndef find_black_position_with_three_non_black_neighbors(input: np.ndarray) -> List[Tuple[int, int]]:\n    \"\"\"\n    This function takes a 2D numpy array as input and returns a list of positions where the color is black and its 3x3 neighborhood contains three non-black positions.\n\n    Args:\n    input: A 2D numpy array representing the input grid.\n\n    Returns:\n    A list of tuples representing the positions where the color is black and its 3x3 neighborhood contains three non-black positions.\n    \"\"\"\n    positions = []\n    for i in range(1, input.shape[0] - 1):\n        for j in range(1, input.shape[1] - 1):\n            if input[i][j] == black and np.sum(input[i - 1:i + 2, j - 1:j + 2] != black) == 3:\n                positions.append((i, j))\n    return positions\ndef is_black_with_one_non_black_neighbor_of_color(input: np.ndarray, position: Tuple[int, int], color: int) -> bool:\n    \"\"\"\n    This function takes a 2D numpy array, a position, and a color as input and returns True if the position is black and its 3x3 neighborhood contains only one non-black position which is equal to the given color.\n\n    Args:\n    input: A 2D numpy array representing the input grid.\n    position: A tuple representing the position to check.\n    color: An integer representing the color to check.\n\n    Returns:\n    A boolean value indicating whether the position is black and its 3x3 neighborhood contains only one non-black position which is equal to the given color.\n    \"\"\"\n    if input[position] != black:\n        return False\n    neighbors = input[position[0] - 1:position[0] + 2, position[1] - 1:position[1] + 2]\n    return np.sum(neighbors != black) == 1 and np.sum(neighbors == color) == 1\ndef change_color(input: np.ndarray, color1: int, color2: int) -> np.ndarray:\n    \"\"\"\n    This function takes a 2D numpy array, two colors as input and returns a new 2D numpy array where all positions with color1 are changed to color2.\n\n    Args:\n    input: A 2D numpy array representing the input grid.\n    color1: An integer representing the color to be changed.\n    color2: An integer representing the new color.\n\n    Returns:\n    A 2D numpy array where all positions with color1 are changed to color2.\n    \"\"\"\n    return np.where(input == color1, color2, input)", "user_code": "def is_55_has_four_non_black_neighbors(input, position, color):\n    if input[position] == black:\n        return False\n    neighbors = input[max(0, position[0] - 2):position[0] + 3, max(0, position[1] - 2):position[1] + 3]\n    return np.sum(neighbors == color) == 3\ndef main(input):\n    positions = find_black_position_with_three_non_black_neighbors(input)\n    origin_color = `find the color in the input, which is not black`(input)\n    input = color_positions(input, positions, origin_color + 1)\n    for i in range(input.shape[0]):\n        for j in range(input.shape[1]):\n            if is_black_with_one_non_black_neighbor_of_color(input, (i, j), origin_color + 1) and is_55_has_four_non_black_neighbors(input, (i, j), origin_color):\n                input = color_positions(input, [(i, j)], origin_color + 1)\n    changed = True\n    while True:\n        changed = False\n        for i in range(input.shape[0]):\n            for j in range(input.shape[1]):\n                if is_color_with_two_non_black_neighbors_of_color(input, (i, j), origin_color + 1):\n                    input = change_neighbor(input, (i, j))\n                    changed = True\n    input = color_positions(input, positions, origin_color)\n    input = change_color(input, origin_color + 1, origin_color)\n    return input", "gpt_code": "def change_neighbor(input: np.ndarray, position: Tuple[int, int]) -> np.ndarray:\n    \"\"\"\n    This function takes a 2D numpy array and a position as input and changes the color of the position's 3x3 neighborhood according to the following rules:\n    - If the upper left corner is not black, color the lower right corner the same color.\n    - If the top right corner is not black, color the bottom left the same color.\n    - If the bottom left corner is not black, color the top right corner the same color.\n    - If the bottom right corner is not black, color the top left corner the same color.\n\n    Args:\n    input: A 2D numpy array representing the input grid.\n    position: A tuple representing the position to change.\n\n    Returns:\n    A 2D numpy array with the color of the position's 3x3 neighborhood changed according to the rules above.\n    \"\"\"\n    color = input[position]\n    if position[0] > 0 and position[1] > 0 and (input[position[0] - 1][position[1] - 1] != black):\n        input[position[0] + 1][position[1] + 1] = input[position[0] - 1][position[1] - 1]\n    if position[0] > 0 and position[1] < input.shape[1] - 1 and (input[position[0] - 1][position[1] + 1] != black):\n        input[position[0] + 1][position[1] - 1] = input[position[0] - 1][position[1] + 1]\n    if position[0] < input.shape[0] - 1 and position[1] > 0 and (input[position[0] + 1][position[1] - 1] != black):\n        input[position[0] - 1][position[1] + 1] = input[position[0] + 1][position[1] - 1]\n    if position[0] < input.shape[0] - 1 and position[1] < input.shape[1] - 1 and (input[position[0] + 1][position[1] + 1] != black):\n        input[position[0] - 1][position[1] - 1] = input[position[0] + 1][position[1] + 1]\n    return input\ndef find_non_black_color(input: np.ndarray) -> int:\n    \"\"\"\n    This function takes a 2D numpy array as input and returns the color in the input, which is not black.\n\n    Args:\n    input: A 2D numpy array representing the input grid.\n\n    Returns:\n    An integer representing the color in the input, which is not black.\n    \"\"\"\n    colors, counts = np.unique(input, return_counts=True)\n    non_black_colors = colors[colors != black]\n    if len(non_black_colors) == 1:\n        return non_black_colors[0]\n    else:\n        raise ValueError('Input contains more than one non-black color.')\ndef is_color_with_two_non_black_neighbors_of_color(input: np.ndarray, position: Tuple[int, int], color: int) -> bool:\n    \"\"\"\n    This function takes a 2D numpy array, a position, and a color as input and returns True if the position is not black and its 3x3 neighborhood contains only two non-black positions which are equal to the given color.\n\n    Args:\n    input: A 2D numpy array representing the input grid.\n    position: A tuple representing the position to check.\n    color: An integer representing the color to check.\n\n    Returns:\n    A boolean value indicating whether the position is not black and its 3x3 neighborhood contains only two non-black positions which are equal to the given color.\n    \"\"\"\n    if input[position] == black:\n        return False\n    neighbors = input[position[0] - 1:position[0] + 2, position[1] - 1:position[1] + 2]\n    return np.sum(neighbors != black) == 2 and np.sum(neighbors == color) == 2\ndef color_positions(input: np.ndarray, positions: Tuple[Tuple[int, int]], color: int) -> np.ndarray:\n    \"\"\"\n    This function takes a 2D numpy array, a list of positions, and a color as input and returns a new 2D numpy array where all positions in the list are changed to the given color.\n\n    Args:\n    input: A 2D numpy array representing the input grid.\n    positions: A list of tuples representing the positions to change.\n    color: An integer representing the new color.\n\n    Returns:\n    A 2D numpy array where all positions in the list are changed to the given color.\n    \"\"\"\n    for pos in positions:\n        input[pos] = color\n    return input\ndef find_black_position_with_three_non_black_neighbors(input: np.ndarray) -> List[Tuple[int, int]]:\n    \"\"\"\n    This function takes a 2D numpy array as input and returns a list of positions where the color is black and its 3x3 neighborhood contains three non-black positions.\n\n    Args:\n    input: A 2D numpy array representing the input grid.\n\n    Returns:\n    A list of tuples representing the positions where the color is black and its 3x3 neighborhood contains three non-black positions.\n    \"\"\"\n    positions = []\n    for i in range(1, input.shape[0] - 1):\n        for j in range(1, input.shape[1] - 1):\n            if input[i][j] == black and np.sum(input[i - 1:i + 2, j - 1:j + 2] != black) == 3:\n                positions.append((i, j))\n    return positions\ndef is_black_with_one_non_black_neighbor_of_color(input: np.ndarray, position: Tuple[int, int], color: int) -> bool:\n    \"\"\"\n    This function takes a 2D numpy array, a position, and a color as input and returns True if the position is black and its 3x3 neighborhood contains only one non-black position which is equal to the given color.\n\n    Args:\n    input: A 2D numpy array representing the input grid.\n    position: A tuple representing the position to check.\n    color: An integer representing the color to check.\n\n    Returns:\n    A boolean value indicating whether the position is black and its 3x3 neighborhood contains only one non-black position which is equal to the given color.\n    \"\"\"\n    if input[position] != black:\n        return False\n    neighbors = input[position[0] - 1:position[0] + 2, position[1] - 1:position[1] + 2]\n    return np.sum(neighbors != black) == 1 and np.sum(neighbors == color) == 1\ndef change_color(input: np.ndarray, color1: int, color2: int) -> np.ndarray:\n    \"\"\"\n    This function takes a 2D numpy array, two colors as input and returns a new 2D numpy array where all positions with color1 are changed to color2.\n\n    Args:\n    input: A 2D numpy array representing the input grid.\n    color1: An integer representing the color to be changed.\n    color2: An integer representing the new color.\n\n    Returns:\n    A 2D numpy array where all positions with color1 are changed to color2.\n    \"\"\"\n    return np.where(input == color1, color2, input)", "holes": {"change_neighbor": "This function takes a 2D numpy array and a position as input and changes the color of the position's 3x3 neighborhood according to the following rules:\n- If the upper left corner is not black, color the lower right corner the same color.\n- If the top right corner is not black, color the bottom left the same color.\n- If the bottom left corner is not black, color the top right corner the same color.\n- If the bottom right corner is not black, color the top left corner the same color.", "find_non_black_color": "find the color in the input, which is not black", "is_color_with_two_non_black_neighbors_of_color": "This function takes a 2D numpy array, a position, and a color as input and returns True if the position is not black and its 3x3 neighborhood contains only two non-black positions which are equal to the given color.", "color_positions": "This function takes a 2D numpy array, a list of positions, and a color as input and returns a new 2D numpy array where all positions in the list are changed to the given color.", "find_black_position_with_three_non_black_neighbors": "This function takes a 2D numpy array as input and returns a list of positions where the color is black and its 3x3 neighborhood contains three non-black positions.", "is_black_with_one_non_black_neighbor_of_color": "determine if the position is black, and its 3*3 neighbors contains only one non-black position which is equal to colorThis function takes a 2D numpy array, a position, and a color as input and returns True if the position is black and its 3x3 neighborhood contains only one non-black position which is equal to the given color.", "change_color": "change the positions which are color1 to color2"}}
